---
import DocPage from '../../../components/DocPage.astro'; import CodeBlock from '../../../components/CodeBlock.astro'; import Callout from '../../../components/Callout.astro';
const test = `using Gua.Testing;
using Gua.Testing.Godot;

using var host = GodotSceneTestHost.Load(
    "res://Main.tscn",
    new GodotSceneTestHostOptions {
        ProjectPath = projectPath,
        UseAvailableBridgePort = true,
        StartupResetPolicy = GuaResetPolicy.Strict,
        TeardownResetPolicy = GuaResetPolicy.Strict,
    });

GuaAssertions.GetByRole(
    host.Context, "button", "Start Game"
).ToBeVisible();

await GuaAssertions.GetById(
    host.Context, "start"
).ClickAsync();

await GuaAssertions.WaitForTextAsync(
    host.Context, "loading", "Loading..."
);`;
---
<DocPage eyebrow="GODOT / TESTING" title="Testing UI" lead="Launch a Godot process and connect to its live semantic UI tree. Locate controls by role, text, and ID, then wait for observable results instead of clicking coordinates." description="Test live Godot scenes with Gua.Testing.Godot." section="godot">
  <h2>1. Install the required NuGet packages</h2><p>External Godot tests require all three packages: <strong>Gua.Core, Gua.Testing, and Gua.Testing.Godot</strong>. Run these commands in the test project directory. Add <code>--version 0.12.0</code> when you want to pin the current release line.</p><CodeBlock title="PowerShell" lang="powershell" code={`dotnet add package Gua.Core --version 0.12.0\ndotnet add package Gua.Testing --version 0.12.0\ndotnet add package Gua.Testing.Godot --version 0.12.0\n\n# When using NUnit\ndotnet add package Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk\ndotnet add package NUnit\ndotnet add package NUnit3TestAdapter`} /><Callout title="What each package owns"><p><code>Gua.Core</code> provides the runtime boundary, <code>Gua.Testing</code> adds locators, waits, and assertions, and <code>Gua.Testing.Godot</code> starts the Godot process and connects to its WebSocket bridge.</p></Callout><p>If Godot is not on <code>PATH</code>, set its executable explicitly.</p><CodeBlock title="PowerShell" lang="powershell" code={`$env:GODOT_EXECUTABLE = "C:\\path\\to\\Godot_v4.7-stable_mono_win64_console.exe"\ndotnet test YourGame.Tests.csproj`} />
  <h2>2. Launch and operate a scene semantically</h2><CodeBlock title="TitleScreenTests.cs" lang="csharp" code={test} />
  <Callout kind="tip" title="Click is a request, not completion"><p><code>Click()</code> enqueues a request. The adapter consumes it on a later frame and routes it through normal input. Follow the click with a <code>WaitFor...</code> call that observes the intended outcome.</p></Callout>
  <h2>3. Operate forms</h2><CodeBlock title="Correlated asynchronous actions" lang="csharp" code={`var name = GuaAssertions.Query(host.Context)\n    .ByRole("textbox").Within("LoginForm").Get();\n\nawait name.SetValueAsync("alice");\nawait name.FocusAsync();\nawait GuaAssertions.PressKeyAsync(host.Context, "Enter");\nawait GuaAssertions.GetById(host.Context, "RememberMe")\n    .SetCheckedAsync(true);\nawait name.WaitForValueAsync("alice");`} />
  <h2>Four rules for reliable tests</h2><div class="grid-2"><div class="mini-card"><strong>Use an available port</strong><p>Set <code>UseAvailableBridgePort = true</code> to avoid collisions in parallel runs.</p></div><div class="mini-card"><strong>Reset strictly</strong><p>Detect leaked requests and events at startup and teardown.</p></div><div class="mini-card"><strong>Wait for state</strong><p>Wait for nodes, values, or stable snapshots instead of sleeping for a fixed time.</p></div><div class="mini-card"><strong>Keep failure evidence</strong><p>Capture the UI tree, logs, stdout/stderr, and optional PNG evidence.</p></div></div>
  <h3>1. Reserve a port per test</h3><p>If every test uses <code>8765</code>, only one Godot process can bind it during a parallel run. Let the host reserve a loopback port and pass it to the child as <code>GUA_BRIDGE_PORT</code>.</p><CodeBlock title="Launch on an available port" lang="csharp" code={`using var host = GodotSceneTestHost.Load(
    "res://Main.tscn",
    new GodotSceneTestHostOptions
    {
        ProjectPath = projectPath,
        UseAvailableBridgePort = true,
    });

// The reserved URL is assigned to the child and RemoteContext.`} />
  <h3>2. Reset strictly before and after the test</h3><p>Do not carry nodes, requests, or events from one test into the next. A strict teardown reports unconsumed work instead of silently deleting it.</p><CodeBlock title="Strict isolation" lang="csharp" code={`using var host = GodotSceneTestHost.Load(
    "res://Main.tscn",
    new GodotSceneTestHostOptions
    {
        ProjectPath = projectPath,
        UseAvailableBridgePort = true,
        StartupResetPolicy = GuaResetPolicy.Strict,
        TeardownResetPolicy = GuaResetPolicy.Strict,
        CaptureDiagnosticsBeforeTeardown = true,
        CleanupAfterLeakReport = true,
    });`} /><Callout kind="tip" title="Convenience preset"><p>Use <code>GodotSceneTestHostOptions.StrictIsolation</code> as the baseline when its defaults are sufficient. Use the explicit form above when you also need a project path and an available port.</p></Callout>
  <h3>3. Wait for observed state, not elapsed time</h3><p><code>Task.Delay(1000)</code> wastes time on a fast machine and may still be too short on a slow one. Wait directly for the state that should follow the action.</p><CodeBlock title="State-based synchronization" lang="csharp" code={`await GuaAssertions.GetById(host.Context, "start")
    .ClickAsync();

// Re-fetch snapshots until the node is visible.
await GuaAssertions.WaitForVisibleAsync(
    host.Context,
    "loading",
    timeout: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(3),
    pollInterval: TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(20));

// Optionally require three unchanged rendered frames.
await GuaAssertions.WaitForStableSnapshotAsync(
    host.Context,
    stableFrames: 3);`} /><Callout kind="warn" title="Avoid fixed sleeps"><p>Do not place a definitive assertion immediately after <code>await Task.Delay(1000);</code>. Express the condition with <code>WaitForVisibleAsync</code>, <code>WaitForTextAsync</code>, <code>WaitForValueAsync</code>, or another state-specific wait.</p></Callout>
  <h3>4. Capture diagnostics when an assertion fails</h3><p>Write the final UI tree, operation history, logs, and Godot stdout/stderr to <code>artifacts/gua</code>. In CI, upload that directory as a test artifact.</p><CodeBlock title="Enable failure diagnostics" lang="csharp" code={`using var diagnostics = host.CreateDiagnosticsSession(
    TestContext.CurrentContext.Test.FullName,
    outputDirectory: Path.Combine(
        TestContext.CurrentContext.WorkDirectory,
        "artifacts", "gua"));

using var assertionScope = GuaAssertionScope.Use(
    new GuaAssertionOptions
    {
        DiagnosticsSession = diagnostics,
    });

// A failure preserves the primary exception and writes diagnostics.
GuaAssertions.GetByRole(
    host.Context, "button", "Start Game"
).ToBeVisible();`} /><p>With GitHub Actions, pass <code>artifacts/gua/**</code> to <code>actions/upload-artifact</code> after the test step so evidence remains available from a failed run.</p>
  <h2>Run tests with GitHub Actions</h2><p>The public <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua-tester"><code>link1345/gua-tester</code></a> action installs Godot on a Windows runner, links the latest released Gua add-on, sets <code>GODOT_EXECUTABLE</code>, and runs <code>dotnet test</code>.</p><CodeBlock title=".github/workflows/godot-gdscript.yml" lang="yaml" code={`name: Godot Gua UI tests

on:
  pull_request:
  push:
    branches: [main]

jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: windows-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - name: Run Gua UI tests
        uses: link1345/gua-tester@v1.2
        with:
          project-path: game
          test-project: tests/GuaTester.Tests.csproj
          godot-version: "4.7"
          godot-status: stable`} /><Callout kind="tip" title="Use the released add-on"><p>The action downloads a ZIP from the latest matching <code>godot-plugin-*</code> release and places it at <code>game/addons/gua</code>. It does not build Gua's native extension in the consumer workflow. See the <a href="/en/docs/github-actions/">GitHub Actions reference</a> for every input and output.</p></Callout>
</DocPage>
